The 'cnoc' is often spoken of in prose and poetry,--'Cnoc na comhairle,'
hill of counsel; 'cnoc na droch comhairle,' hill of evil counsel; 'duine
cnocach,' a shrewd man; 'duine cnocach cruaidh,' a shrewd hard man; 'cho
glic ri cnoc,' as wise as a council knoll; 'cho glic ri leanabh cnoc
ais,' as wise as the child of the knoll of wisdom.

